According to this regression, when the 20% list is in effect, private school students have a 2.6% greater chance than non-private school students of being assigned to a prestige school. This effect could be considered substantial given that private primary school students constitute a very small population.

This effect is NOT significant at the p<0.05 level when students' composite SEA scores are controlled for. Therefore, I am not able to find a statistically significant relationship and fail to reject the null to my hypothesis. The evidence does not suggest that attending a private primary school increases the likelihood of being assigned to a prestige school.

